00:21:30,580 --> 00:21:34,983
Or you're against the wall with performance, and that could be a problem.

365
00:21:35,364 --> 00:21:41,328
It could be font size is too small, and there's literally not enough room on the screen to fit everything at a font size that's legible.

366
00:21:41,948 --> 00:21:44,230
It really varies.

367
00:21:44,870 --> 00:21:46,811
It really depends on your situation.

368
00:21:46,871 --> 00:21:52,415
It's just important to try to consider it at the beginning, because pretty much anything can be expensive if added in too late.

369
00:21:54,715 --> 00:22:01,978
While we're waiting, I will also say the custom controls can be difficult to cover at the last minute as well, so please also keep that in mind.

370
00:22:03,099 --> 00:22:11,802
Roger that. Oh, that's a good point. Yeah, I'll read the question I just sent to Karen. What is a topic you didn't have time to cover in your talk that you would like developers to hear?

371
00:22:11,822 --> 00:22:11,863
Um,

372
00:22:14,644 --> 00:22:19,286
So for my talk, one thing I would like to overemphasize is that when you're doing

373
00:22:20,857 --> 00:22:27,897
When you're considering what API to use to make a synthetic voice, keep in mind that most platforms have them already.

374
00:22:28,707 --> 00:22:34,368
So, like, Apple has voiceover, Windows has narrator. It is possible to use that in your games.

375
00:22:34,749 --> 00:22:38,070
Like, I was the tech lead for all the games that came with Windows 7 back from Microsoft,

376
00:22:38,350 --> 00:22:42,351
and all those games had the ability to be menu narrated, even though they were all

377
00:22:42,571 --> 00:22:47,913
DirectX-based. And it is possible to do that, and it's not as hard as you think.

378
00:22:48,533 --> 00:22:52,154
So, keep that in mind that you can actually, like, make conceptual overlays.

379
00:22:53,054 --> 00:22:58,438
Keep in mind that when you're working with blind accessibility that the way people navigate

380
00:22:58,478 --> 00:23:02,060
things can be different than when you don't have the feature turned on.

381
00:23:02,400 --> 00:23:07,063
You'll notice that Windows Narrator itself makes Windows behave differently because it's

382
00:23:07,123 --> 00:23:10,705
assuming keyboard-based navigation, not mouse-based navigation.

383
00:23:11,125 --> 00:23:16,509
And I really, really strongly recommend turning on narration on your own local platforms that

384
00:23:16,529 --> 00:23:17,229
you're implementing on.

385
00:23:17,960 --> 00:23:20,962
especially if it's Windows or a phone or a tablet,

386
00:23:21,583 --> 00:23:24,865
to see how it's navigated and how it works.

387
00:23:25,325 --> 00:23:27,347
Because I'll give you a lot more information right there

388
00:23:27,467 --> 00:23:28,668
as to how to use your game,

389
00:23:28,788 --> 00:23:29,948
or how to implement that in your game.

